---HEADER---
file:                  tooling/spec_router.py
language:              python
role:                  Subcommand 'spec --topic TOPIC'. Maps a short
                       topic keyword to the corresponding SPEC/NN_*.md
                       module and prints its content directly. Saves
                       sessions from reading LLMISLAND_SPEC.md's topic
                       table just to find the right module.
layer:                 io
status:                verified
confidence:            high (rationale: authored fresh in rc6, smoke-
                       tested for all 14 SPEC/ files via topic keys)
generation-pass:       false
read-reason:           task-driven
last-verified:         v0.3-2026-05-07
maintained-by:         llm
exports:
  - SPEC_TOPIC_MAP
  - cmd_spec
  - setup_spec
  - SUBCOMMANDS
imports:
  - argparse
  - pathlib                   :: Path
  - tooling.common            :: find_project_root
  - tooling.types             :: Finding, Report
depends-on:
  - llmisland_tooling.py      :: orchestrator iterates SUBCOMMANDS
  - SPEC/                     :: every keyword maps to a SPEC/NN_*.md
                                 file; missing files produce a Report
                                 with code spec-file-missing
translation-boundary:  none
dynamic-boundary:      false

---SYMBOLS---

SYMBOL: SPEC_TOPIC_MAP
kind:           constant
pure:           true
total:          true
latency-budget: N/A
effects:
  reads:    none
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   one dict at import time (~60 entries)
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - cmd_spec :: lookup
  - error message :: lists keys when topic is unknown
calls:
  - none
expects:
  - keys are normalized (lowercase, no separators)
  - values are SPEC/ filenames that exist on disk
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet — first test pass should assert every value
              corresponds to an existing SPEC/ file
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    medium (rationale: filenames are hardcoded; renaming a
                                  SPEC/ module silently breaks every
                                  matching topic key)
fragility-note: when SPEC/ modules are renamed, the rename cascades
                here. validate.py (rc8) should add a check that every
                value in this map resolves to an existing file.

SYMBOL: cmd_spec
kind:           function
pure:           false (reads filesystem, prints to stdout)
total:          true
latency-budget: <50ms (one file read)
effects:
  reads:    filesystem (one SPEC/ file)
  mutates:  stdout when not in --json mode
  allocs:   one string for file content
  throws:   never (returns Report on errors)
  async:    false
  io:       filesystem read, stdout
called-by:
  - llmisland_tooling.main :: dispatch when args.command == 'spec'
calls:
  - _normalize         :: input cleanup
  - _resolve_topic     :: lookup with fuzzy fallback
  - find_project_root  :: locate SPEC/ when --spec-dir absent
  - Path.read_text     :: load file content
expects:
  - args has .topic (str), .spec_dir (str|None), .json (bool, from
    parent parser)
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    medium (rationale: dual return type — int for direct
                                  print path, Report for --json /
                                  error paths. A future change must
                                  preserve both branches.)
fragility-note: contract subcommand-return-shape (mainland) permits
                int OR Report. spec returns int 0 in the print-and-
                exit path because wrapping the SPEC/ module content
                in a Report would force the caller to extract it.
                With --json, returns Report so the content is in the
                summary as a string, machine-parseable.

SYMBOL: setup_spec
kind:           function
pure:           true (mutates parser passed in)
total:          true
latency-budget: <1ms
effects:
  reads:    none
  mutates:  argparse.ArgumentParser
  allocs:   none meaningful
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - llmisland_tooling.build_parser
calls:
  - parser.add_argument
expects:
  - parser supports add_argument
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

SYMBOL: SUBCOMMANDS
kind:           constant
pure:           true
total:          true
latency-budget: N/A
effects:
  reads:    none
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   one dict at import time
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - llmisland_tooling.build_parser :: iterates module.SUBCOMMANDS
calls:
  - none
expects:
  - {'spec': (setup_spec, cmd_spec, helptext)} shape
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

---RISKS---

security:                none
regression-sensitivity:
  - renaming any SPEC/ module silently breaks every matching topic key
    in SPEC_TOPIC_MAP; mitigate by adding a startup assertion in rc8
    validate.py
platform-sensitivity:
  - file content is decoded as UTF-8 with errors='replace'; on Windows
    consoles without UTF-8 the orchestrator wraps stdout (see
    llmisland_tooling.py.llmisland). Without that wrap, Unicode
    characters in spec content would crash on Windows cp1252.
config-dependencies: none

---MEMORY---

ACTIVE-CONSTRAINTS:
  - id: AC-001
    constraint:  every value in SPEC_TOPIC_MAP must correspond to an
                 existing file under SPEC/. The set of distinct values
                 should equal the set of SPEC/NN_*.md filenames.
    established: 2026-05-04
    evidence:    smoke test: ran spec --topic for one key per file in
                 rc6; all resolved correctly

  - id: AC-002
    constraint:  cmd_spec must return int 0 in the print-and-exit
                 path, NOT a Report. Wrapping the content in a Report
                 would force callers to extract it. The orchestrator
                 dispatcher accepts either return type per contract
                 subcommand-return-shape.
    established: 2026-05-04
    evidence:    contract subcommand-return-shape

HISTORICAL-DECISIONS:
  - id: HD-001
    decision:  print spec content directly when --json is absent
    reason:    the user wants to see the spec module, not a JSON
               wrapper around it. Wrapping in a Report would make
               text output noisy: "[ok] spec\n  summary:\n    content:
               <thousands of lines>".
    date:      2026-05-04
    outcome:   stable; --json still returns Report so machine-
               parseable use cases work
    evidence:  inferred-from-design

  - id: HD-002
    decision:  fuzzy substring matching as fallback when exact lookup
               fails
    reason:    LLMs and humans both type partial keywords. Returning
               an unambiguous match for "stat" -> "status" is helpful;
               returning "ambiguous" for "stat" -> ["status", "stale",
               "staleness"] is honest. The matcher prefers exact then
               unique-substring then unambiguous-failure-with-list.
    date:      2026-05-04
    outcome:   stable
    evidence:  inferred-from-design

  - id: HD-003
    decision:  --topic is required, not optional
    reason:    'spec' with no topic has no useful default. Either
               print everything (defeats the purpose) or print
               nothing (silent). Required is clearer.
    date:      2026-05-04
    outcome:   stable
    evidence:  inferred-from-design

SUPERSEDED:
  - none yet
